#2.1 Simple Message: Assign a message to a variable, and then print that message.
message = "Yuvi you will be a billionare soon!"
print(message)

#2.2 Simple Messages: Assign a message to a variable, and print that message. Then change the value of your variable to a new message, and print the new message.
message = "Yuvi you will be a billionare soon!"
print(message)

message = "Yuvi just keep the hustle on!"
print(message)

message = "Yuvi success is not far away!"
print(message)

#2.3 Personal Messsage: Store a person's name in a variable, and print a message to that person. Your message should be simple, such as, "Hello Yuvi, did you get better today than yesterday?"
Yuvi = "Yuvi You are doing great, keep it up!"
print(Yuvi)

#2.4 Name Cases: Store a person's name and then print that person's name in uppercase and lowercase.
mere_bhagwan = "radhekrishna"
print(mere_bhagwan.lower())
print(mere_bhagwan.upper())

#2.5 Famous Quote: Find a quote from a famous person you admire. Print the quote and name.

My_fav_quote = '''Premanand Maharaj said, "Jiske saath bhagwan ho uska koi kya hi bigaad sakta hai"'''
print(My_fav_quote)

#2.6 Famous Quote 2: Repeat Exercise 2.5, but this time store the famous person's name. Then compose your own message and print it.

Apj_Abdul_Kalam = "The darker the night, the brighter the days is!"
print(Apj_Abdul_Kalam)

#2.7 Stripping names: Store a person's name, and include some whitespace characters at the beginning and end of the name. Make sure you use each character combination, "\t" and "\n", at least once. Print the name once, so the whitespace around the name is displayed. Then print the name using each of the three stripping functions, lstrip(), rstrip(), and strip().

name = "  Radha  "
print(name)
print(name.lstrip())
print(name.rstrip())
print(name.strip())

#2.8 File extensions: Python has a removesuffix method that works exactly like removeprefix(). Assign the value 'python.py' to a variable, and then use the removesuffix() method to print the file extension of the value.

file = "python.py"
print(file.removesuffix(".py"))

#2.8 Number Eight: Write addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations that each result in the number 8. Be sure to enclose your operations in print() calls to see the results.

print(4+4)
print(10-2)
print(4*2)
print(16/2)

#2.9 Favourite Number: Use a variable to represent your favourite number. Then, using that variable, create a message that reveals your favourite number. Print that message.

fav_number = 12
print(f"My favourite number is {fav_number}.")

#2.10 Adding Comments: Choose two of the programs you've written, and add at least one comment to each. 

#This is a program which outputs the value 8 in each case(i.e add, sub, mul, div)
print(4+4)
print(10-2)
print(4*2)
print(16/2)

#This is a program which stirps the whitespace from left, right and both sides of the string.
name = "  Radha  "
print(name)
print(name.lstrip())
print(name.rstrip())
print(name.strip())

